<HEADLINE>
COA DEPUTY CHAIRMAN STABLE AFTER SUFFERING STROKE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taichung, Jan. 1 (CNA) 01/01/07  19:16:31 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
Council of Agriculture (COA) Vice Chairman Lin Kuo-hua was listed
in stable condition Monday after receiving surgery at a Taichung
hospital to remove blood clots from his brain that caused a
stroke.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin's family, Lin felt dizzy and nauseous early
Sunday and was immediately taken to the Yunlin branch of National
Taiwan University Hospital, where he lapsed into a coma.
</P>
<P>
Doctors diagnosed that he had suffered a hemorrhagic stroke and
showed a blood coagulation disorder. They suggested that he be
transferred to Taichung Veterans General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
After detecting that the 71-year-old COA deputy chairman had
blood clots in his brain, a medical team at the Taichung hospital
operated on him and removed about 200 c.c. of congealed blood.
</P>
<P>
Lin regained consciousness Monday and was recovering in an
intensive care unit. Doctors said he was able to move his
previously paralyzed limbs on the left side after the operation.
</P>
<P>
President Chen Shui-bian paid Lin a visit at the hospital to wish
him a speedy recovery.
</P>
